body:
If we do `subprocess.run('conda activate resnet')`, conda will not be well initialized, and causing the problem in #38. To solve this, I added a prefix for the user command executed in `subprocess.run`. It is similar to what ray did in [here](https://github.com/ray-project/ray/blob/c5175073b27426fb176847fb0c2b89df2c4a0f1e/python/ray/_private/runtime_env/conda_utils.py#L15). Current code passed `run_smoke_test.sh`. 

One concern is whether we need this in the backend or should we let the users do the `. $(conda info --base)/etc/profile.d/conda.sh` in their app. The latter one will make the single- and multi-task experience different since the single task utilizes the `ray exec` to start the cmd and will not raise the conda uninitialized issue.  

@michaelzhiluo could you please check if this will change the behavior of distributed training (hopefully it can solve the missing package problem with horovord)?
